  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite its publication over two decades ago, \"Social Dimensions of U.S. Trade Policies\" remains relevant within the academic community, reflected by its citation count of 35. The work's focus on policy sustainability aligns it with contemporary discussions surrounding various social dynamics in trade.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by the University of Michigan Press in 2000, \"Social Dimensions of U.S. Trade Policies\" provides an insightful examination of the intricate relationships between trade policies and social factors in the United States. The text has garnered scholarly attention with a citation count of 35, underscoring its influence within academic discussions related to trade and policy analysis.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">One notable aspect of this work is its implications for sustainability and policy relevance. With a strength of 0.55 in this area, the book contributes to broader conversations about sustainable practices in trade policies and their social dimensions, highlighting its alignment with current global discourse on sustainability.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's legacy extends beyond its original publication, as it continues to inform research and policy debates more than 20 years later. Its focus on the social implications of trade offers a framework for understanding contemporary issues, reinforcing its sustained significance within the literature. Scholars who cite this work often do so in contexts that examine the intersection of trade and society, indicating a strong uptake in relevant fields.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although there is a lack of contemporary online discourse or mentions across social media platforms, the academic citation metrics affirm that it remains a relevant resource for researchers exploring trade policies. The ongoing scholarly engagement reflects the book's durability and foundational contributions to the field of social and trade studies.</p>",
